                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d149">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">868.00/12–544: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-05T14:00:00+02:00"
                            >December 5, 1944—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 9—2:52 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>129. I have authorized the Foreign Office to deny reports printed in yesterday’s
                    Leftist press according to which I had protested to <pb facs="0155" n="143"
                        xml:id="pg_143"/> my British colleague both verbally and in writing against
                    British interference in Greek affairs. These inventions [<hi rend="italic"
                        >interventions?</hi>] would appear not unconnected with the recent
                    publication by the same press of an alleged statement by the Secretary
                    concerning our Government’s policy of nonintervention (see my No. 120 of
                    December 3, 6 p.m.) and perhaps represent a policy to play up America’s neutral
                    attitude in contrast to British intervention here. While doing all I can not to
                    allow this Mission to become involved in internal affairs, I have also been
                    careful so far as possible not to embarrass our British Allies and my British
                    colleague realizes this as well as the extreme delicacy of the position
                    involved.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
